How can you communicate
and condense that

00:22:53.030 --> 00:22:55.850
into just words in an
encyclopedia or perhaps just

00:22:55.850 --> 00:22:57.180
some diagrams?

00:22:57.180 --> 00:22:59.800
And the only
encyclopedia compilers,

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:03.354
and there's a blog post on
exactly this on the website,

00:23:03.354 --> 00:23:06.020
they were acutely aware, perhaps
even more so than we are today,

00:23:06.020 --> 00:23:09.430
of just how fragile and
vulnerable civilizations are.

00:23:09.430 --> 00:23:12.007
The Roman Empire collapsed, the
Greek civilization collapsed,

00:23:12.007 --> 00:23:14.465
the Mayans and Incans, which
we've discovered subsequently,

00:23:14.465 --> 00:23:17.280
have all collapsed.

00:23:17.280 --> 00:23:19.470
So what could you do
to preserve the sum

00:23:19.470 --> 00:23:20.550
total of human knowledge?

00:23:20.550 --> 00:23:23.700
And they made genuine attempts
to record everything back then.

00:23:23.700 --> 00:23:25.770
We know a bit more
nowadays, so that

00:23:25.770 --> 00:23:28.660
would be perhaps impossible, and
even something like Wikipedia

00:23:28.660 --> 00:23:31.630
doesn't even come close.

00:23:31.630 --> 00:23:34.785
So the conceit, the kind of
cheeky answer, if you like,

00:23:34.785 --> 00:23:38.040
up the website is you would
get an iPad or another kind

00:23:38.040 --> 00:23:41.730
of tablet, you would
jerry-rig with a solar panel

00:23:41.730 --> 00:23:44.630
or an alternator from a car to
regenerate power for yourself

00:23:44.630 --> 00:23:46.305
and recharge your
batteries, and you

00:23:46.305 --> 00:23:48.138
would download some of
the apps I recommend.

00:23:48.138 --> 00:23:50.610
We can rip off, scoop
off videos from YouTube,

00:23:50.610 --> 00:23:52.619
and save them on this
hard disk of your tablet.

00:23:52.619 --> 00:23:54.910
So when the internet goes
down, which will happen very,

00:23:54.910 --> 00:23:57.319
very quickly after the
apocalypse, you've still got,

00:23:57.319 --> 00:23:59.110
not just the words of
"The Knowledge" book,

00:23:59.110 --> 00:24:02.110
but also these
kind of demo videos

00:24:02.110 --> 00:24:04.060
stored for prosperity
as it were.

00:24:07.214 --> 00:24:08.880
AUDIENCE: Well, I was
just going to ask,

00:24:08.880 --> 00:24:10.680
do you think we might
have been in a better

00:24:10.680 --> 00:24:14.350
position to reinvent [INAUDIBLE]
maybe a hundred years ago

00:24:14.350 --> 00:24:15.260
before the internet?

00:24:15.260 --> 00:24:18.380
Because the internet
makes people's minds lazy,

00:24:18.380 --> 00:24:19.780
and you don't have
to know stuff,

00:24:19.780 --> 00:24:21.690
because you can look
it up on the internet.

00:24:21.690 --> 00:24:24.989
And so, therefore, that's how
civilization spread early,

00:24:24.989 --> 00:24:27.280
orally being passed down from
generation-to-generation,

00:24:27.280 --> 00:24:29.547
skills, stories,
mythologies, et cetera.

00:24:29.547 --> 00:24:31.130
LEWIS DARTNELL: Yeah,
my gut reaction,

00:24:31.130 --> 00:24:33.830
my impression is that we'd
probably be worse off today

00:24:33.830 --> 00:24:36.610
than a century ago if this
hypothetical scenario were

00:24:36.610 --> 00:24:39.162
to happen, if you do have
to go back to scratch.

00:24:39.162 --> 00:24:40.870
Because even during
the Second World War,

00:24:40.870 --> 00:24:43.078
there was an enormous amount
of ingenuity and problem

00:24:43.078 --> 00:24:46.380
solving during the scarcity
of the Second World War,

00:24:46.380 --> 00:24:48.670
and most people had an
allotment in the back garden,

00:24:48.670 --> 00:24:49.961
and they grew stuff themselves.

00:24:49.961 --> 00:24:52.330
They grew vegetables and
food to feed themselves.

00:24:52.330 --> 00:24:53.830
How many of us do that today?

00:24:53.830 --> 00:24:54.330
No.

00:24:54.330 --> 00:24:55.930
There's perhaps not
that many hipsters

00:24:55.930 --> 00:24:58.310
in London that have even
got access to an allotment

00:24:58.310 --> 00:24:59.340
to be able to grow.

00:24:59.340 --> 00:25:00.500
And I did try when
I was living down

00:25:00.500 --> 00:25:02.166
in Angel to get an
allotment for myself,

00:25:02.166 --> 00:25:04.720
and there was something like
a nine-year waiting list.

00:25:04.720 --> 00:25:07.640
So all of these skills
are just dissolving away.

00:25:07.640 --> 00:25:09.490
They're disappearing.

00:25:09.490 --> 00:25:12.480
You don't repair things
for yourself anymore.

00:25:12.480 --> 00:25:15.400
You can't get your
radio and take out

00:25:15.400 --> 00:25:17.640
the valve that isn't working
anymore and replace it.

00:25:17.640 --> 00:25:20.500
You can't look and understand
the mechanism of the things

00:25:20.500 --> 00:25:21.970
we use, because--

00:25:21.970 --> 00:25:23.970
You know, your iPhone,
the mechanism inside that

00:25:23.970 --> 00:25:25.610
is literally visibly small.

00:25:25.610 --> 00:25:28.630
You'd need a microscope to be
able to see the kind of city

00:25:28.630 --> 00:25:30.686
landscape of the
circuitry there.

00:25:30.686 --> 00:25:33.310
And it's not something that you
could ever repair for yourself.

00:25:33.310 --> 00:25:34.380
And in fact, you're
not even expected

00:25:34.380 --> 00:25:36.020
to take the back off
technology nowadays.

00:25:36.020 --> 00:25:37.436
You just take it
back to the shop,

00:25:37.436 --> 00:25:40.820
and a genius will
repair it for you.

00:25:40.820 --> 00:25:42.249
And I think that's sad.

00:25:42.249 --> 00:25:44.790
I think it's lamentable we're
losing that connection with how

00:25:44.790 --> 00:25:47.540
things are made or done
in a fundamental sense.

00:25:53.975 --> 00:25:56.330
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

