00:25:57.490 --> 00:25:57.940
LEWIS DARTNELL: Thank you.

00:25:57.940 --> 00:25:59.000
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:00.490
Two related questions.

00:26:00.490 --> 00:26:03.690
As you went through all
of your research for this,

00:26:03.690 --> 00:26:06.620
and you were focusing on
things that we were missing,

00:26:06.620 --> 00:26:10.466
were there any kind of objects
or processes that you thought,

00:26:10.466 --> 00:26:11.380
you know what?

00:26:11.380 --> 00:26:13.670
Actually, we could
just forget that.

00:26:13.670 --> 00:26:19.230
And kind of related to that,
are there any social constructs

00:26:19.230 --> 00:26:25.550
that you came across that you
thought how would we implement

00:26:25.550 --> 00:26:28.122
law or government
or whatever it is?

00:26:28.122 --> 00:26:30.205
LEWIS DARTNELL: Yeah, so,
two very good questions.

00:26:32.770 --> 00:26:35.310
One of the recurring themes I
tried to keep coming back to

00:26:35.310 --> 00:26:37.550
through the book
was this network,

00:26:37.550 --> 00:26:39.880
this web of scientific
discoveries,

00:26:39.880 --> 00:26:42.650
which enable you to make new
technological innovations,

00:26:42.650 --> 00:26:44.280
which then allow
you to investigate

00:26:44.280 --> 00:26:46.739
the world in a new way and make
new scientific discoveries.

00:26:46.739 --> 00:26:48.988
So that kind of back-and-forth
process between science

00:26:48.988 --> 00:26:51.490
and technology and exploring
this vast web of knowledge we

00:26:51.490 --> 00:26:52.440
have today.

00:26:52.440 --> 00:26:54.547
So for example, mastering
the substance of glass

00:26:54.547 --> 00:26:56.630
and grinding it into a
lens to build a microscope,

00:26:56.630 --> 00:26:59.610
which allows you to explore
the invisible realm.

00:26:59.610 --> 00:27:02.394
But with hindsight, we
now know red herrings

00:27:02.394 --> 00:27:04.810
we took in history, science,
and technology, or stuff that

00:27:04.810 --> 00:27:07.190
turn out to be not all
that very useful, or things

00:27:07.190 --> 00:27:10.010
like electricity that
are so useful in so

00:27:10.010 --> 00:27:12.290
many different ways you
want to beeline directly

00:27:12.290 --> 00:27:14.130
to that gateway
technology, as I call it,

00:27:14.130 --> 00:27:16.750
and it opens up a whole
load of other stuff.

00:27:16.750 --> 00:27:19.040
So there's a video about
electrolysis on the website,

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:21.350
about how you can use
electricity not just for power

00:27:21.350 --> 00:27:23.430
and moving things
with motors for you,

00:27:23.430 --> 00:27:25.630
but generating
crucial substances,

00:27:25.630 --> 00:27:27.980
like bleach or
chlorine and things.

00:27:27.980 --> 00:27:30.600
So you want to leapfrog
something like electricity

00:27:30.600 --> 00:27:32.590
and the printing press
for similar reasons

00:27:32.590 --> 00:27:35.230
and also the social
ramifications of that.

00:27:35.230 --> 00:27:37.474
But, it being a
popular science book,

00:27:37.474 --> 00:27:39.140
and already being
quite difficult to fit

00:27:39.140 --> 00:27:41.581
all the scientific knowledge
into just 300 pages,

00:27:41.581 --> 00:27:43.830
one of the early decisions,
one of the early editorial

00:27:43.830 --> 00:27:46.690
decisions was to leave out
more of the social sciences,

00:27:46.690 --> 00:27:51.850
the politics and economics
and a description

00:27:51.850 --> 00:27:54.180
of how to build a
democracy from scratch.

00:27:54.180 --> 00:27:56.960
Because, while undeniably
important, I think

00:27:56.960 --> 00:27:59.810
there's a clear distinction
between art and music

00:27:59.810 --> 00:28:03.850
and politics and science, and
that science is universal.

00:28:03.850 --> 00:28:06.920
The laws will be true no matter
where you are or when you are.

00:28:06.920 --> 00:28:10.020
Humanity will have the same
requirements and demands

00:28:10.020 --> 00:28:11.910
that technology
must provide for.

00:28:11.910 --> 00:28:14.890
So science and technology,
in a sense, are universal,

00:28:14.890 --> 00:28:17.350
but politics isn't really.

00:28:17.350 --> 00:28:20.710
And my suspicion was if I wrote
this twee little 10-step guide

00:28:20.710 --> 00:28:23.395
to building a parliamentary
democracy, it doesn't matter,

00:28:23.395 --> 00:28:24.770
because whoever's
got the biggest

00:28:24.770 --> 00:28:26.440
gun gets to be the boss anyway.

00:28:26.440 --> 00:28:28.398
And they're not going to
relinquish their power

00:28:28.398 --> 00:28:30.240
unless you go
through, perhaps, 100,

00:28:30.240 --> 00:28:33.600
200 years of social
revolution and slow change.

00:28:33.600 --> 00:28:38.280
So you can provide key kernels
or principles of science,

00:28:38.280 --> 00:28:41.640
but you can't really do the same
thing for social constructs.

00:28:41.640 --> 00:28:44.277
I think they have to arise
organically or naturally.

00:28:44.277 --> 00:28:46.360
And it probably wouldn't
make that much difference

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:48.920
if you described democracy,
because it would-- no one would

00:28:48.920 --> 00:28:51.500
pay any attention unless
they're ready for it anyway.

00:28:51.500 --> 00:28:53.550
You'd perhaps live
with a feudal system

00:28:53.550 --> 00:28:54.950
for 50 years or whatever.

00:28:54.950 --> 00:28:56.420
MALE SPEAKER: Time for one more.

